HEADWORD: Forcible-feeble
<hw>For"ci*ble-fee`ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From
<ets>Feeble</ets>, a character in the Second Part of Shakespeare's
⟦ldquo⟧King Henry IV.,⟦rdquo⟧ to whom Falstaff derisively applies the
epithet ⟦ldquo⟧<ets>forcible</ets>.⟦rdquo⟧]</ety> <def>Seemingly
vigorous, but really weak or insipid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Prof. Ayton] would purge his book of much offensive matter, if
he struck out epithets which are in the bad taste of the
<qex>forcible-feeble</qex> school.</q> <rj><qau>N. Brit.
Review.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forcibleness</ent>⟦br⟧
